This house supports the government facilitating the integration of parallel societies into mainstream society

A parallel society arises when a distinct group within a country—often defined by ethnicity, religion, or culture—lives largely apart from the mainstream, operating with its own norms, institutions, and informal systems of governance. These communities may establish separate schools, media, or justice mechanisms, and have limited interaction or integration with broader society. Examples include immigrant suburbs in France with informal Islamic structures, Sharia councils in parts of the UK, segregated Roma settlements in Eastern Europe, or Amish communities in North America.
